06531nam a22008415i 9780774833363DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748333637 a10.59962/97807748333632doi  a(DE-B1597)662213  a(OCoLC)1394871842  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ1075 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a305.3/0971/09045223  aLB 446052rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90559:98200aWe Still Demand! :bRedefining Resistance in Sex and Gender Struggles /ced. by Gary Kinsman, Patrizia Gentile, L. Pauline Rankin. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (324 p.) :b9 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSexuality Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tHistories of Resistance and Activism -- tLiberating Marriage -- t“Seducing the Unions” -- t“À bas la répression contre les homosexuels!” -- tFire, Passion, and Politics -- tThe Emergence of the Toronto Dyke March -- tRupert Raj, Transmen, and Sexuality -- tQueer Resistance and Regulation in the 1970s -- tThe Politics and Power of Resistance -- t“A History of That Which Was Never Supposed to Be Possible” -- t“Your Cuntry Needs You” -- tSafe Sex Work and the City -- t“Collateral Damage” -- tNationalism, Sexuality, and the Politics of Anti-Citizenship -- tTrans-ing the Canadian Passport -- tSelected Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe Still Demand! recovers vibrant and unsung histories of sex and gender activism across Canada from the 1970s to the present. Departing from conventional accounts, this book demonstrates the varied nature of resistance and the productive power of remembering sex and gender struggles. In attending to the records and accounts that have slipped out of view, it also redraws the boundaries between activism and scholarship. The first part of the book remembers these struggles. Drawing on a rich history of activism, the contributors recall 1970s same-sex marriage activism; early queer union organizing; organizing against police repression; early trans organizing; the emergence of dyke marches; the organization of black queer space at Toronto Pride events. The second part of the book rethinks past and current struggles. The authors address gender “passing” in historical research; lesbian s/m porn; sex-worker organizing; problems with organizing against “human trafficking”; queer immigration and refugee struggles; and trans identity. By recovering the history of activism and outlining contemporary challenges, We Still Demand! provides a vital rewriting of the history of sex and gender activism that will enlighten current struggles and activate new forms of resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGay peoplexPolitical activityzCanadaxHistory. 0aGay rightszCanadaxHistory. 0aGaysxPolitical activityzCanadaxHistory. 0aProstitutesxPolitical activityzCanadaxHistory. 0aSex rolexPolitical aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSex rolexPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aSex rolezCanadaxHistory. 0aTransgender peoplexPolitical activityzCanadaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aBain, Beverly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrûlé, Mathieu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurgess, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChenier, Elise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerris, Shawna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGentile, Patrizia, econtributor.4ctb4